column1: "WITHIN A TWENTY INCH SQUARE AREA, USING A BLACK, HARD CRAYON, DRAW TEN THOUSAND FREEHAND LINES, OF ANY LENGTH, AT RANDOM. PRINT THIS IN FOUR COLORS (BLACK, RED, BLUE AND YELLOW) BY TURNING THE STONE A QUARTER TURN FOR EACH COLOR.", from the portfolio WORK FROM INSTRUCTIONS
column3: One from a portfolio of ten lithographs

column1: "USING A BLACK, HARD CRAYON DRAW A STRAIGHT LINE OF ANY LENGTH. FROM ANY POINT ON THAT LINE DRAW ANOTHER LINE PERPENDICULAR TO THE FIRST. FROM ANY POINT ON THE SECOND LINE DRAW ANOTHER LINE PERPENDICULAR TO THAT LINE. REPEAT THIS PROCEDURE.", from the portfolio WORK FROM INSTRUCTIONS
column3: One from a portfolio of ten lithographs

column1: "USING A BLACK, HARD CRAYON, DRAW FOUR CONTIGUOUS TEN INCH SQUARES, FORMING ONE TWENTY INCH SQUARE, DIVIDED INTO QUARTERS. WITHIN THE FIRST SQUARE (UPPER LEFT) DRAW ONE LINE, ONE INCH LONG. WITHIN THE SECOND SQUARE (UPPER RIGHT) DRAW TEN LINES, EACH ONE INCH LONG.  WITHIN THE THIRD SQUARE (LOWER LEFT) DRAW ONE HUNDRED LINES, EACH ONE INCH LONG.  WITHIN THE FOURTH SQUARE (LOWER RIGHT) DRAW ONE THOUSAND LINES, EACH ONE INCH LONG.  ALL LINES SHOULD BE AT RANDOM AND STRAIGHT.", from the portfolio WORK FROM INSTRUCTIONS
column3: One from a portfolio of ten lithographs

column1: "USING A BLACK, HARD CRAYON DRAW A TWENTY INCH SQUARE, DIVIDE THIS SQUARE INTO ONE INCH SQUARES. WITHIN EACH ONE INCH SQUARE, DRAW NOTHING OR A FREE HAND LINE OR LINES." from the portfolio WORK FROM INSTRUCTIONS
column3: One from a portfolio of ten lithographs

column1: The World War had caused a great shortage in Northern industry and also citizens of foreign countries were returning home
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: In many of the communities the Negro press was read continually because of its attitude and its encouragement of the movement
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: Another of the social causes of the migrants' leaving was that at times they did not feel safe, or it was not the best thing to be found on the streets late at night. They were arrested on the slightest provocation
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: Child labor and a lack of education was one of the other reasons for people wishing to leave their homes
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: And people all over the South began to discuss this great movement
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: The labor agent who had been sent South by Northern industry was a very familiar person in the Negro counties
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: In every home people who had not gone North met and tried to decide if they should go North or not
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: The railroad stations in the South were crowded with people leaving for the North
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: The Negro press was also influential in urging the people to leave the South
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: They arrived in great numbers into Chicago, the gateway of the West
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: They also worked in large numbers on the railroad
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: The Negro was the largest source of labor to be found after all others had been exhausted
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: The migrants arrived in great numbers
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: They also made it very difficult for migrants leaving the South. They often went to railroad stations and arrested the Negroes wholesale, which in turn made them miss their train
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: Living conditions were better in the North
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: Industries attempted to board their labor in quarters that were oftentimes very unhealthy. Labor camps were numerous
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: Housing for the Negroes was a very difficult problem
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: Race riots were very numerous all over the North because of the antagonism that was caused between the Negro and white workers. Many of these riots occurred because the Negro was used as a strike breaker in many of the Northern industries
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: One of the largest race riots occurred in East St. Louis
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: One of the main forms of social and recreational activities in which the migrants indulged occurred in the church
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: Among one of the last groups to leave the South was the Negro professional who was forced to follow his clientele to make a living
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: In the North the Negro had better educational facilities
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: The trains were packed continually with migrants
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy
Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: They did not always leave because they were promised work in the North. Many of them left because of Southern conditions, one of them being great floods that ruined the crops, and therefore they were unable to make a living where they were
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy
Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: The railroad stations were at times so over-packed with people leaving that special guards had to be called in to keep order
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: Among the social conditions that existed which was partly the cause of the migration was the injustice done to the Negroes in the courts
column5: Gift of Mrs. David M. Levy

column1: Although the Negro was used to lynching, he found this an opportune time for him to leave where one had occurred
